passages.text: Reiterating OW as MacroScenario continues to Improve, Offsetting Potential Micro Headwinds

We are updating our estimates for Brazilian Malls (MULT, IGTI and ALOS) and establishing our Dec- 26 PT, which are on average \(15\%\) above our previous targets. We continue to flag that the sector's performance remains highly correlated to real rates; therefore our OW is supported by JPM's bullish view on rates for 2026YE at \(10.75\%\) vs consensus at \(\sim 13.9\%\) , with cuts already starting this year. On the bottom- up front, our positive view is justified by: i) Attractive upside of \(33 - 34\%\) to our Dec- 26 PTs; ii) Spread of 310bps to long- term real rates vs historical levels of \(\sim 180\) bps (10Y); and iii) Tailwinds from non- core operations such as land plot sales, real estate development and media results. We are making small changes to our estimates, increasing FFO per share by \(6 - 9\%\) for 2026 reflecting mostly higher than expected top- line. We maintain our relative preference of MULT \(>\) IGTI \(>\) ALOS. We favor low- income homebuilders vs. malls as 2H25 should be relatively stronger as the sector counts on continuous support from the MCMV program, while Malls' results should be impacted by softer IGPM.

Malls as a Macro play. When looking at the sector's historical performance over the past 4 easing cycles, Malls have outperformed the IBOV in intervals of 1 month, 3M, 6M and 12M after the last Selic hike. The biggest outperformance happened 12M after the last hike at \(\sim 21\) pp on average. In the periods of 1M, 3M and 6M, the sector outperformed IBOV by 2- 3pp. Therefore, assuming that the last hike happened in June this year, the sector still has an outperformance of at least \(\sim 17\) pp until June 2026 (12M after the last Selic hike) in order to reach the average historical outperformance.

Outlook for 2H25. On a bottom- up approach, we don't expect the sector to have major catalysts during 2H as on its core business - rents - IGPM slowdown and retail accommodation should limit top- line growth, while parking and services should also have more limited growth.

Small relative preference for MULT, as usually stocks move together with YTD performance at \(+28 - 29\%\) vs IBOV at \(+16\%\) . Our relative preference for MULT is supported by: i) Superior asset quality and governance justifying its premium valuation of \(10.0x\) P/FFO 26e; ii) Relatively higher own GLA expansion at \(+2\%\) by 2027 YE vs peers \(- 3\%\) to \(- 5\%\) (vs 2024 levels); and iii) Potential cancellation of up to \(\sim 24.6\) mn shares held in treasury \((- 5\%)\) of outstanding shares). IGTI is our \(2^{\mathrm{nd}}\) top pick reflecting the quality and location of its premium assets, followed by ALLOS the high beta play in the sector in case of additional divestments, which would drive higher distribution and value creation to shareholders.

We see the sector trading at a spread of 310bps to long-term real rates, with YTD Performance at \(+28 - 29\%\) YTD vs Homebuilders at \(+30 - 90\%\) and IBOV at \(+16\%\) , and compared with the 10Y rate down 10bps YTD. Current spreads represent a high post-COVID-19, limiting further downside. Moreover, the beginning of the Selic easing cycle should act as a potential trigger for a re-rate, as our economic team expects cuts to start already this year. Even though we believe the spread between malls' FFO yield and long-term real rates will remain above the historical average of \(-180\) bps due to higher levels of real rates and lower GLA growth, we see the current level as exaggerated as we expect the spread to return to around \(-200 - 250\) bps.
Figure 1: Spread - Bz Malls FFO Yield and 10Y Real Interest Rates
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P., company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

Valuation details: When comparing Malls' current and historical spreads between FFO yields and long- term real interest rates (10Y), IGTI is trading at the highest discount to historical levels (10Y) at a \(-80\%\) discount vs. MULT at \(-20\%\) and ALOS at a discount of \(50\%\) . In our view MULT lower spread reflects its stronger results over the past quarters as well as its asset quality.

When looking at sector performance during an easing cycle, based on the last 4 cycles, the Malls have on average outperformed the IBOV by 21pp in the 12 months post the last Selic hike. Considering that June 2025 was the last hike in the current cycle, the sector still has an outperformance of at least 16pp to IBOV to reach its average alpha.
Figure 2: Brazilian Malls Outperformance vs IBOV 12M after last hike on Selic - There is still \(\sim 16\) pp of alpha to be generated assuming past cycles average outperformance (21pp) Rally vs IBOV
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Bloomberg Finance L.P.

We expect the own GLA CAGR (2024- 2027e) of listed names to stand between \(- 2\%\) to \(+1\%\) , underscoring the sector's dependence on positive leasing spreads and alternative revenue streams to deliver top- line growth. Worth flagging that even though Iguatemi has executed M&A transactions as of late (Rio Sul, Patio Higienopolis and Patio Paulista, adding \(\sim 19k \mathrm{m}^2\) in own GLA), its portfolio by year- end should stand at 457k given the sale of stakes in Galleria and Shopping Market Place (total of \(\sim 26k \mathrm{m}^2\) ). Moreover, ALLOS had implemented an aggressive divestment plan reducing its GLA by around \(6\%\) since the end of 2023.

Additionally, the expected deceleration in IGPM should add pressure to Same Store Rent growth during 2H25 as JPM economists expect 2Q25 level of \(6.6\%\) yoy to reach \(0.7\%\) yoy by 4Q25.
Figure 4: Listed Malls names SSR vs IGPM - Inflation Slowdown to Bring Pressure to Rental Growth YoY (%)
Source: Company reports and J.P.Morgan estimates. IGPM with 1 quarter lag to better match contracts adjustments.
Over the past years, as all 3 names have ramped- up initiatives in non- core segments in order to accelerate growth, in the bullets below we summarize companies' main initiatives:

- Multiplan: Residential Golden Lake project in Porto Alegre that will total a PSV of R\$4.9bn to be launched within the next decade (R\$950mn already launched), currently representing \(\sim 5\%\) of 2025e EBITDA. According to our calculation, assuming that it would take 10 years for Multiplan to fully develop this PSV, MULT could generate up to R\$735mn in net income considering a \(15\%\) net margin or \(\sim R\) \$530mn at NPV, representing \(\sim 4\%\) of its current market cap.  
- Iguatemi: i-Retail initiative, which acts as an incubator for global brands in Brazil by taking over operations - HR, marketing, IT, and financials, among others - on behalf of retailers. During 1H25 this initiative (alongside e-commerce Iguatemi 365) generated an EBITDA of R\$3.0mn. Moreover, Iguatemi plans to develop until 2038 the Casa Figueira neighborhood, a district with 1mn m², surrounding the Iguatemi
Campinas shopping mall, with a net present value of future revenues generated for IGTI at R\$350- 400mn or \(\sim 5\%\) of its market cap.

- ALLOS: ALLOS subsidiary Helloo (media subsidiary) and NEOOH have won the bid to manage media inventories for 17 Aena airports, including Congonhas. The JV will share estimated revenues of R\$1.4bn over the next 10 years with Aena. Recall that ALLOS's media revenues increased 31% during 2Q25, representing \(\sim 6\%\) of its gross revenues.

Old vs. New & JPMevs ConsensusOverall, FFO per share estimates are increasing for the 3 companies under our coverage for 2026 by \(6 - 9\%\) reflecting an increase of \(1 - 5\%\) on top line and better financial results due to the companies' better- than- expected results during 2Q, which included in the case of MULT land bank sales, while in the case of IGTI divestment from Galleria and Market Place it helped to lower the mid- term leverage. Keep in mind that for ALOS and MULT we are not adjusting our FFO per share for shares held in treasury as they have not been canceled yet; adjusting these figures, our FFO per share would be around \(5\%\) higher for MULT and \(8\%\) higher for ALOS.
Table 5:Old vs.New Estimates (R\$mn)
Source:J.P.Morgan estimates.

While for MULT our numbers are pretty much aligned with consensus, with FFO per share \(- 1\%\) to \(+2\%\) vs consensus, in the case of IGTI we are significantly above consensus (up to \(+11\%\) ), helped by stronger top- line incorporating recent M&A activity and J.P. Morgan's bullish view on Selic, with cuts to start this year with Selic reaching \(10.75\%\) by 4Q26. More importantly, when comparing IGTI's 2026 FFO to their compiled consensus, our number is \(4\%\) below their expectations. For ALOS, our number for 2026 is also pretty much aligned with consensus.
Table 6:J.P.Morgan vs.Consensus Estimates (R\$mn)
Source:Bloomberg Finance L.P.,J.P.Morgan estimates.
Iguatemi (Overweight; Price Target: \(R\) 30.00)

Our Overweight on IGTI is supported by: i) Attractive upside of \(34\%\) to our Dec- 26 PT, ii) Attractive valuation as the stock is trading at 8.8x P/FFO 12M fwd. representing a spread of \(\sim 390\) bps to 10Y real rates vs a historical (10Y) average of \(\sim 220\) bps; ii) Potential synergies from recently acquired assets such as RioSul, Patio Paulista and Patio Higienopolis; and iii) Improving operational results, reflecting the quality of its assets given its exposure to high income class and the turnaround on Iguatemi 365 which has a growing positive contribution to the company's EBITDA. Additionally, IGTI is developing some residential projects such as the Casa Figueira residential project in Campinas which should start to positively impact results in the mid term. Moreover, Market Place multifamily - sold to a \(3^{\mathrm{rd}}\) party - should help to increase results in this asset.

We have an Overweight rating on Iguatemi and a Dec- 26 price target of \(R\) 30.00, which derives from our DCF valuation in which we assume a COE in US \(\) of 12.0\%\(based on a beta of 1.00, country risk of 3.5%, a risk - free rate of 3.0%, and an equity risk premium of 5.5%. In our price target, we are including -\) R\) 0.50 per share to reflect the potential of its land bank.
ALLOS (Overweight; Price Target: \(R\) 31.00)

We rate ALLOS Overweight. Positives include: i) Cheapest relative valuation in the sector trading at a spread of \(\sim 420\) bps to the 10Y real rate and \(8.6x\) P/FFO 12M Fwd., reflecting its lower than peers tenant sales over the past quarters as the high income segment has been outperforming; ii) Attractive yield of \(\sim 10\%\) for 2025e including dividends plus buybacks, which we expect to remain around these levels, assuming additional divestment opportunities; iii) Bottom- up story given: a) Divestments at accretive cap rates and the synergies post- BRML merger that bring upside potential, and b) Successful loyalty and malls & media programs that benefit from the company's large scale and geographic diversification.

In our Dec- 26 price target, we did not include the potential expansion of \(\sim 54k m^2\) of GLA in projects announced last year - Carioca \((1.1k m^2)\) , Taboão \((16.6k m^2)\) , Bahia \((10.1k m^2)\) , Bangu \((2.7k m^2)\) , Franca \((10.2k m^2)\) , Campo Limpo \((6.7k m^2)\) , Parque Dom Pedro \((4.9k m^2)\) , and Leblon \((1.6k m^2)\) - due to the lack of information regarding the capex and opening dates. In our model, we include only Maceio expansion of \(2.75k m^2\) at ALLOS stake and Campo Grande expansion at \(12.2k m^2\) \((71\%\) owned by ALOS) and that should be concluded by 2027. We have included in our Dec- 26 price target \(\sim R\) 2.00 per share to reflect the company's land bank potential at net present value.

We have a Dec- 26 price target of \(R\) 31.00 based on our DCF valuation, considering a cost of equity of \(12.0\%\) in USD, a beta of 1.0, a country risk of \(3.5\%\) , a risk- free rate of \(3.0\%\) , and an equity risk premium of \(5.5\%\) . We have included in our Dec- 26 price target \(\sim R\) 2.00 per share to reflect the company's land bank potential at net present value, for contracts signed worth \(R\) 433mn as well as, the existing potential of \(1.6mn m^2\) available on its land bank. ALOS holds 43mn shares in treasury, around \(8\%\) of total outstanding shares, if canceled it would increase our Dec- 26 PT to \(R\) 34.00.
Multiplan (Overweight; Price Target: R\(36.00)

Our Overweight rating on Multiplan reflects the company's quality portfolio (superior sales/m \(^2\) ), corporate governance, and its ability to continue posting growth in periods of sluggish IGP- M through other revenue streams such as services and residential projects developments (Golden Lake). Moreover, Multiplan has well- located malls owning premium and dominant assets in several of Brazil's main capitals, which serve as a destination for consumers, justifying its premium valuation vs. peers. In our model, we are only including Morumbi, Maceio and Brasilia, totaling almost \(20k m^2\) of own GLA (around \(+3\%\) vs current own GLA), as these expansions have disclosed capex levels and have been officially launched.

We rate Multiplan Overweight with a Dec- 26 price target of R\(36.00 based on our DCF valuation, in which we assume a COE of 11.2% based on a beta of 0.85, country risk of 3.5%, a risk- free rate of 3.0%, and an equity risk premium of 5.5%. Our price target also includes R\)2.00 per share for the potential to develop multiuse projects with the company's land bank. Keep in mind that MULT still holds \(\sim 25m\) shares in treasury that if canceled would increase our Dec- 26 PT to R\(38.00.
